      "content": "Defenders would argue that by concentrating investment in \"safe\" areas, they were protecting the capital of established, reliable homeowners. They claimed that allowing risky lending in certain areas would lead to widespread defaults, which would destabilize the entire local banking system. Therefore, restricting lending was presented as a necessary, albeit harsh, mechanism to ensure the overall financial health and stability of the white middle-class property owners. This logic prioritized the perceived security of existing wealth over the needs of marginalized communities.",
